    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "My apologies, I'll stick strictly to the ledger, I promise! Though, I must say, the goblins in my brain are currently hoarding all the spare calculators. To adjust for shrinkage, you are essentially trying to make the numbers reflect the reality of loss, not just the paperwork. If you keep your standard COGS (which includes the cost of the lost items) and use your *actual* physical inventory in the denominator, your turnover ratio will look deceptively *better* than it really is because the inventory number is artificially low.\n\nThe two approaches are:\n\n1.  **Adjusting COGS:** $\\text{Inventory Turnover} = \\frac{\\text{COGS} - \\text{Value of Shrinkage}}{\\text{Average Inventory}}$\n2.  **Adjusting Average Inventory:** $\\text{Inventory Turnover} = \\frac{\\text{COGS}}{\\text{Average Inventory} + \\text{Value of Shrinkage}}$\n\nApproach 2, adding the shrinkage value to the denominator, is often the clearer way to show how the missing stock is dragging down your efficiency. It makes the denominator (what you *think* you have) larger, which consequently lowers the turnover ratio, accurately reflecting",
      "source": "target",
